{"key":"processedPost-8909157","value":{"id":8909157,"first":8908934,"last":8911339,"when":1221100689,"utime":"09/11/08 05:38 AM","content":"In the early 70's when I lived in the Dallas area, I used to drive my pickup to the rich neighborhoods in highland park to collect their grass clippings.&nbsp; They have gardeners and golf course looking lawns, so the bags of clippings weighed 70 pounds or more, and they would stack them neatly by the curb.<br /><br />I'd compost them for my garden.&nbsp; This is when I first discovered mushrooms, and buried several active cow patties around the perimeter of the compost pile after one of my trips to east texas where they're everywhere.&nbsp; Long story short, I forgot all about that experiment until fall when the rains hit, and I literally had hundreds, if not thousands of cubes pop all around the pile.&nbsp; Been addicted to growing ever since.<br /><br />I doubt they'd work as well uncomposted, but you can always try.&nbsp; They're not like straw, which is hollow.<br />RR","title":"Re: Lawn clippings as a bulk-sub","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}